# GitHub Copilot Frontend Engineering Rules  

**Scope:** Enterprise-grade, production frontend systems  
**Target:** VS Code + GitHub Copilot  
**Primary Stack:** Next.js (App Router), React, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, ES2023+  

This document defines **mandatory engineering standards** that GitHub Copilot must follow when generating frontend code.  
All output must be **scalable, performant, accessible (WCAG 2.2 AA+), secure, SEO-safe, and production-ready**.

---

## 1. General Coding Principles

### Naming Conventions
- **Components:** `PascalCase` (`UserProfileCard`)
- **Hooks:** `useX` prefix (`useUserSession`)
- **Utilities:** `camelCase`
- **Folders:** `kebab-case`
- **Booleans:** `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`

---

### File & Folder Structure
- Feature-based architecture is mandatory
- No folder nesting beyond 3 levels
- Colocate files with primary usage
- Avoid unnecessary barrel exports

```

app/
components/
ui/
shared/
features/
auth/
dashboard/
lib/
api/
utils/
types/
styles/

```

---

### Readability & Consistency
- One responsibility per function/component
- Early returns preferred
- No deeply nested logic
- Max function length: 40 lines
- Max component length: 300 lines
- No mixed architectural patterns

---

### Commenting Philosophy
- Explain **why**, never **what**
- Mandatory for:
  - Business logic
  - Security decisions
  - Performance trade-offs

---

## 2. Project Architecture Rules

### Next.js App Router
- App Router only
- Server Components by default
- Client Components only when strictly required
- Data fetching on server whenever possible

---

### Separation of Concerns
- **UI Layer:** Rendering & interactions
- **Domain Layer:** Business logic
- **Data Layer:** APIs, caching, persistence
- No cross-layer coupling

---

### Shared vs Feature Components
- Shared:
  - Stateless
  - Generic
- Feature:
  - Domain-aware
  - Encapsulated logic

---

## 3. React Rules

### Component Rules
- Functional components only
- No class components
- One component per file
- Composition over inheritance

---

### Hooks Usage
- Hooks at top-level only
- No conditional hooks
- One concern per hook

---

### Custom Hooks
- Logic-only (no JSX)
- Reusable and minimal API
- Predictable return shape

---

### State Management
- Prefer local state
- Lift state only when required
- Global state only with strong justification
- Server state libraries for remote data

---

### Controlled Components
- Forms must be controlled
- Uncontrolled only for performance-critical cases

---

### Memoization
- Use `useMemo` / `useCallback` only when measurable
- Avoid premature optimization

---

### Context
- Small, focused contexts only
- Never use context for high-frequency updates

---

## 4. TypeScript Rules

### Strict Typing
- `strict: true` mandatory
- No implicit `any`
- No unsafe type assertions

---

### No `any` Policy
- `any` is forbidden
- Use `unknown` with narrowing

---

### Interface vs Type
- `interface` for public contracts
- `type` for unions and utilities

---

### Utility Types
- Prefer built-in utility types
- Custom utilities only if reusable

---

### Type Inference
- Allow inference internally
- Explicit typing for public APIs

---

### API Typing
- Typed request & response
- Validate all external data
- Never trust backend blindly

---

## 5. Styling Rules (Tailwind CSS)

### Utility-First
- Tailwind only
- No inline styles
- No arbitrary values without justification

---

### Class Composition
- Use `clsx` or `cva`
- Avoid long class strings

---

### Responsive Design
- Mobile-first
- Explicit breakpoints
- No desktop-only logic

---

### Design Tokens
- Colors, spacing, typography via config
- No hardcoded values

---

### Theming
- CSS variables
- Centralized theme control

---

### Dark / Light Mode
- System preference support
- No duplicated components

---

## 6. Performance Rules (MANDATORY)

Performance is **non-negotiable**.

---

### Code Splitting
- Route-based splitting mandatory
- Feature-level splitting for large domains
- Shared components must remain tree-shakable

---

### Lazy Loading
- Use `next/dynamic` responsibly
- Lazy-load heavy, non-critical UI
- Always provide fallback
- No CLS allowed
- Never lazy-load critical UI or navigation

---

### Images
- Use `next/image` exclusively
- Always define `width`, `height`, `sizes`
- `priority` only for LCP images
- Prefer AVIF / WebP

---

### Bundle Control
- Avoid heavy dependencies
- Prefer native APIs
- Tree-shakable imports only
- Regular bundle audits

---

### Rendering
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Stable props and keys required
- No side effects during render

---

## 7. Accessibility & SEO Rules (MANDATORY)

**Target:** WCAG 2.2 AA+  
**Accessibility is a hard requirement, not optional.**

---

### Semantic HTML
- Semantic elements by default
- No div-only layouts

---

### ARIA
- Use only when semantic HTML is insufficient
- No redundant roles

---

### Labels
All inputs MUST have:
- `<label>`, OR
- `aria-label`, OR
- `aria-labelledby`

---

### Buttons & Links
- Use `<button>` and `<a>` only
- Icon-only buttons MUST have `aria-label`
- No clickable divs or spans

---

### Keyboard Navigation
- All interactive elements keyboard-accessible
- Logical tab order
- No keyboard traps

---

### Focus Management
- Visible focus styles required
- Trap focus in modals
- Restore focus on close

---

### Headings
- One `<h1>` per page
- No skipped heading levels

---

### Images (a11y)
- Meaningful images require `alt`
- Decorative images must use `alt=""`

---

## SEO Rules
- Semantic landmarks required:
  - `header`, `nav`, `main`, `footer`
- Descriptive links only
- No duplicate H1
- Structured data preferred when applicable

---

## 8. API & Data Handling

### Fetching
- Server-side fetching by default
- Client fetching only when interactive

---

### Error Handling
- Graceful UI fallback
- No silent failures

---

### Loading States
- Skeletons preferred
- Avoid spinners for long loads

---

### Caching & Revalidation
- Cache aggressively
- Invalidate intentionally
- Use ISR / tags appropriately

---

## 9. Security Rules

### XSS Prevention
- Never use `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`
- Sanitize all external content

---

### Input Validation
- Validate at UI & API boundaries
- Schema-based validation required

---

### Token Handling
- No tokens in `localStorage`
- HttpOnly cookies preferred

---

### Environment Variables
- No secrets in client bundle
- Runtime validation required

---

## 10. Testing Rules

### Unit Tests
- Pure logic only
- No DOM access

---

### Component Tests
- Test behavior, not implementation
- Accessibility assertions required

---

### E2E Tests
- Critical user flows only
- Stable selectors required

---

### Mocking
- Mock boundaries only
- Avoid over-mocking

---

## 11. Linting & Formatting

### ESLint
- Zero warnings policy
- Strict rules enforced

---

### Prettier
- Single formatting source
- No manual formatting

---

### Import Order
- External → internal → relative
- Alphabetical order enforced

---

## 12. Git & Workflow Rules

### Commit Messages
```

type(scope): concise description

```

---

### Branch Naming
```

feature/short-description
fix/bug-description

```

---

### Pull Requests
- Clear description
- Screenshots required
- Performance impact noted

---

### Review Checklist
- Performance
- Accessibility
- Security
- Scalability

---

## 13. Documentation Rules

### Components
- Props documented
- Usage examples required

---

### API Docs
- Typed contracts
- Error states documented

---

### README
- Setup
- Architecture
- Conventions

---

### Storybook
- UI components only
- No business logic

---

## 14. AI-Specific Rules (Copilot Behavior)

### Code Generation
- Production-ready only
- Follow architecture strictly

---

### Must Avoid
- Deprecated APIs
- Inline hacks
- Premature optimization

---

### Preferred Patterns
- Composition
- Explicit contracts
- Predictable data flow

---

### Anti-Patterns
- God components
- Global mutable state
- Side effects in render

---

### Output Formatting
- Clean, minimal
- No placeholder TODOs
- No unnecessary explanations

---

**End of Rules**